koha-starman-worker-watcher (0.5.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Drop runtime_threshold_seconds. Alerts now fire on memory crossing
    alone, for every Starman worker over memory_threshold_mb (still
    one-shot per PID lifetime). The previous "idle" filter skipped
    workers whose proctitle was still "starman worker ..." — but that
    proctitle is also what REST API requests and plain Plack handlers
    run under, so bloated workers doing real work could evade alerting.
    The filter is gone; an empty script path is now rendered "(none)"
    in alerts and logs.
  * kill_runtime_threshold_seconds is now a dwell time: a worker must
    sustain RSS above memory_threshold_mb for this many seconds before
    being killed. If the worker drops below memory_threshold_mb at any
    scan, the dwell clock resets. kill_memory_threshold_mb, when set,
    is an additional current-RSS gate ANDed with the dwell check.
    Existing configs that only set kill_memory_threshold_mb keep
    behaving the same way (kill on current-RSS alone, no dwell).
    runtime_threshold_seconds in existing configs is now ignored.
  * New Koha::StarmanWorkerWatcher::Stack module: installs a SIGUSR2
    handler in plack.psgi that writes a Carp::longmess backtrace to
    <capture.output_dir>/koha-stack-<pid>.txt. The watcher signals the
    worker at capture time, slurps the file into the capture bundle
    (and Slack tail), and unlinks it. Adds Perl-level file/sub/package
    visibility to captures without requiring debug symbols for libperl
    (which Debian does not ship). Both sides read output_dir from
    config.yaml so the path always agrees. Workers blocked in a
    C-level call fall back to gdb's backtrace as before. Opt-in via
    capture.perl_stack_signal: SIGUSR2's OS default is Term, and
    without the cooperating handler the watcher would kill the worker
    it was trying to inspect. The captures dir is now mode 1777 so
    koha instance users can drop their own dump files there; sticky
    bit keeps non-owners from removing each other's files.
  * Restore strace as an opt-in probe alongside gdb.
    capture.gdb_enabled and capture.strace_enabled are now independent
    toggles, both default false — a fresh install writes a minimal
    .stack.txt with only /proc/<pid>/{wchan,syscall,stack} and no
    ptrace-attaching; operators opt each probe in per host. Both can
    run in the same capture. strace output streams into a gzipped
    <base>.strace.gz sidecar next to the .stack.txt and its tail is
    folded into the main capture and Slack alert. strace is a
    Recommends now that it's optional; gdb stays a hard Depends so
    the probe is always available to turn on.

 -- Kyle M Hall <kyle@bywatersolutions.com>  Mon, 20 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000

koha-starman-worker-watcher (0.4.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * After an auto-kill, grep /var/log/koha/<instance>/ for log lines
    whose timestamp is within ±60s of the kill, filter the OPAC,
    intranet, and plack access logs to 4xx/5xx only (where the 502
    from the killed upstream lands with the culprit URL), bundle the
    result to <instance>-<pid>-<timestamp>-<signal>.logs.txt next to
    the strace capture, and include the access-log matches inline in
    the Slack kill notice. Waits 2s after the signal so Apache has
    time to flush the 502. No configuration knobs; paths and windows
    are hard-coded. New dependency: libpath-tiny-perl.

 -- Kyle M Hall <kyle@bywatersolutions.com>  Fri, 17 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000

koha-starman-worker-watcher (0.3.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Auto-kill: new top-level config keys kill_runtime_threshold_seconds
    and kill_memory_threshold_mb. When at least one is set, workers that
    exceed the configured kill thresholds are SIGTERMed on first
    detection and SIGKILLed on the next scan if still alive. Both
    thresholds are ANDed at evaluation time, but an unset parameter is
    treated as a wildcard (so you can kill on memory alone, runtime
    alone, or both). Each signal is logged and posted to Slack as a
    notice. ignore_scripts/ignore_instances are honored. The startup
    Slack notice now also reports active kill thresholds when set.

 -- Kyle M Hall <kyle@bywatersolutions.com>  Wed, 15 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000

koha-starman-worker-watcher (0.2.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Perl daemon that scans /proc for Koha Starman workers and alerts to
    Slack when a worker exceeds a runtime or memory (RSS) threshold.
  * Resolves Koha instance from the worker's KOHA_CONF environment
    variable, with a fall-back walk up to the starman master parent.
  * Reports RSS and swap in the alert payload; threshold is evaluated
    against RSS only.
  * AND logic: a worker must exceed both runtime_threshold_seconds
    and memory_threshold_mb on the same scan pass before an alert
    fires. Crossing only one threshold is ignored.
  * One alert per PID lifetime; resets on PID reuse.
  * Posts a one-line startup notice to Slack on daemon start when
    slack.webhook_url is set, naming the host and active thresholds.
  * Optional strace capture on alert with streaming gzip output
    (strace -o '|gzip -c > ...'), count-based rotation, and the tail of
    the trace embedded in the Slack message.
  * slack.enabled config toggle for log-only operation — alerts are
    still computed, captures still written, full alert text still
    logged to journald, but no HTTP POST is made.
  * Ships a systemd unit with Restart=always and hardening flags
    (ProtectSystem, ProtectHome, PrivateTmp, CapabilityBoundingSet).
  * Conffile /etc/koha-starman-worker-watcher/config.yaml.

 -- Kyle M Hall <kyle@bywatersolutions.com>  Tue, 14 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000

